@node Indexes
@section Indexes

Indexes improve query performance for common operations.  The following
indexes are recommended for production deployments:

@example
-- Users table
CREATE INDEX idx_users_username ON users(username);
CREATE INDEX idx_users_email ON users(email);

-- Posts table
CREATE INDEX idx_posts_user_id ON posts(user_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_posts_created_at ON posts(created_at DESC);
CREATE INDEX idx_posts_reply_to_id ON posts(reply_to_id);

-- Likes table
CREATE INDEX idx_likes_post_id ON likes(post_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_likes_user_id ON likes(user_id);

-- Follows table
CREATE INDEX idx_follows_follower ON follows(follower_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_follows_following ON follows(following_id);

-- Notifications table
CREATE INDEX idx_notifications_user ON notifications(user_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_notifications_read ON notifications(read);

-- Messages table
CREATE INDEX idx_messages_conversation ON messages(conversation_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_messages_created ON messages(created_at DESC);
@end example

The SQLite query optimizer will automatically use these indexes when
available.  Check query performance using the @code{EXPLAIN QUERY PLAN}
command.

@node Migrations
@section Migrations

The database schema is versioned through a migration system in
@file{backend/src/db.zig}.  Migrations are applied automatically when
the server starts.

New tables are created using @code{CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS}
statements, which ensures idempotency.  Existing tables can be modified
using @code{ALTER TABLE} statements recorded in the schema migrations
array.

To add a new table:

@enumerate
@item
Add a @code{CREATE TABLE} statement to the @code{migrations} array in
@file{db.zig}.

@item
Restart the server.  The migration will be applied automatically.
@end enumerate

@node Backup and Restore
@section Backup and Restore

Because the database is a single file, backup and restore operations
are straightforward.

@subheading Manual Backup

@example
sqlite3 /path/to/xeetapus.db ".backup '/path/to/backup.db'"
@end example

Or simply copy the file:

@example
cp /path/to/xeetapus.db /path/to/backup.db
@end example

It is recommended to stop the server before making backups to ensure a
consistent snapshot.

@subheading Automated Backup

A cron job can automate daily backups:

@example
0 2 * * * sqlite3 /var/www/xeetapus/xeetapus.db ".backup '/var/backups/xeetapus-$(date +\%Y\%m\%d).db'"
@end example

@subheading Restore

To restore from a backup:

@enumerate
@item
Stop the server.

@item
Copy the backup file over the current database:
@example
cp /path/to/backup.db /path/to/xeetapus.db
@end example

@item
Restart the server.
@end enumerate

@subheading Database Maintenance

Periodically run these commands to maintain database performance:

@example
-- Optimize storage
VACUUM;

-- Update query planner statistics
ANALYZE;

-- Check for corruption
PRAGMA integrity_check;
@end example

